Auto Insurance Fraud Claim Identification Prediction ¶

**Goal of the Project**¶

- Develop a model that identifies high potential fraud claims in order to minimize future financial loss (of the insurance company)¶

**Project's Framework**¶

1. Understand the insurance claim data (Exploratory Data Analysis EDA)¶

2. Prepare data to build a model¶

3. Develop model performance measurements¶

4. Apply classification models to the data¶

-- Deep learning techniques are not applied in this project as the dataset is not huge and is already in structured format.¶
Logistic regression¶
KNN (K Nearest Neighbor)¶
Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)¶
Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)¶
Decision Tree¶
Random Forest¶
Ada Boost Classifier¶
Gradient Boosting Classifier¶
Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) Classifier¶

5. Compare performances of the above models and identify a strong candidate models¶

6. Tune hyperparameters of the chosen models (if possible)¶

7. Choose the final model and identify the relative importance of input variables to predict a fraud claims¶

7. Identify relatively importance of the input information to predict fraud claims with a final model¶

8. Develop business recommendations¶

**Findings** ¶

1. Fraud_report Y=25%. This is an unbalanced data.¶

2. Because the purpose of this project is to reduce the false negative case, a recall rate is selected as the main measurement for model performances.¶

3. After hyperparameter tunning, Gradient Boosting Classifier performs the best with the test data recall rate 86%¶

4. Interestingly, main predictors are: Incident_severity (especially when the values are total loss or minor damage), Insured_hobbies (especially when the values are chess or cross-fit) and Vehicle_Claim amount.¶

**Data Source** ¶

Insurance Fraud Detection data from Kaggle - https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arpan129/insurance-fraud-detection¶

# Function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex=True,  # X-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# Function to plot stacked bar plots
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    
    predictor: independent variable
    
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins = True).sort_values(
        by = sorter, ascending = False
    )
    print("<<",predictor," by ",target, ">>")
    
    print(tab1)
    
    print("-" * 80)
    
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize = "index").sort_values(
        by = sorter, ascending = False
    )
    
    tab.plot(kind = "bar", stacked = True, figsize = (count + 1, 5))
    
    plt.legend(
        loc = "lower left",
        frameon = False,
    )
    
    plt.legend(loc = "upper left", bbox_to_anchor = (1, 1))
    
    plt.show()

Decide Model Evaluation Criterion¶

  • False Positive: predict a claim as a fraud, but it turns out that it was not a fraud.
  • False Negative: Identify a claim as a genuine claim, but it turns out that it was a fruad and insurance company lost money.
  • It looks like false negative cases will damage an insurance company more than false positive cases. Therefore, we need to build a model that minimize the false negative or maximize recall of the fraud=1 case.

model evaluation matrix¶

In [25]:
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):

    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = ['Not Fraud', 'Fraud'], yticklabels = ['Not Fraud', 'Fraud'],cmap="PiYG")

    plt.ylabel('Actual')

    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    
    plt.show()
In [26]:
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    
    predictors: independent variables
    
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # Predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    overall_recall = recall_score(target, pred,average = 'macro')                 # To compute recall
    
    overall_precision = precision_score(target, pred, average = 'macro')              # To compute precision
               
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)                                 # To compute accuracy score
    
    f1=f1_score(target, pred, average = 'macro') 
    
    focus_recall = recall_score(target, pred, pos_label=1)
    focus_precision = precision_score(target, pred, pos_label=1)
    focus_f1_score=f1_score(target, pred, pos_label=1)

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {  
            "Overall Precision":  overall_precision,
            "Overall Recall":  overall_recall,
            "Overall Accuracy": acc,
            "Overall F1 Score":f1,
            "focus_precision":focus_precision,
            "focus_recall": focus_recall,
            "focus_F1_score":focus_f1_score

        },
        
        index = [0],
    )

    return df_perf

def relative_plot(model,predictors ):
    
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    columns=predictors.columns
    importance_df = pd.DataFrame(importances, index = columns, columns = ['Importance']).sort_values(by = 'Importance', ascending = False)
    plt.figure(figsize = (13, 13))
    sns.barplot(importance_df.Importance,importance_df.index)
    print(importance_df)
    plt.show()

    'solver': ['svd', 'lsqr', 'eigen'],
    'n_components': [None,1, 2, 3, 4],
    'shrinkage': [None, 'auto'],
    'tol': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01]
}

y_scores_lda_tuned = lda_tuned_2.predict_proba(x_train) 

precisions_lda, recalls_lda, thresholds_lda = precision_recall_curve(y_train, y_scores_lda_tuned[:, 1])

# Plot values of precisions, recalls, and thresholds
# The last precision and recall values are 1. and 0. respectively and do not have a corresponding threshold. 
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 7))

plt.plot(thresholds_lda, precisions_lda[:-1], 'b--', label = 'precision')

plt.plot(thresholds_lda, recalls_lda[:-1], 'r--', label = 'recall')

plt.xlabel('Threshold')

plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')

plt.ylim([0, 1])

plt.show()


# find the meeting point between precision and recall
pre_recl_df = pd.DataFrame()
pre_recl_df['precision'] = precisions_lda[:-1]
pre_recl_df['recall'] = recalls_lda[:-1]
pre_recl_df['threshold'] = list(thresholds_lda)


threshold_point = pre_recl_df['threshold'].loc[pre_recl_df['recall'] ==pre_recl_df['precision']]
print("The new threshold to test is ",threshold_point)

The new threshold to test is  418   0.523

Name: threshold, dtype: float64

--> finding: The new threshold is 0.523 which is almost the same with the default threshold 0.5. No need to proceed further.

Gradient Booster Hyperparameter Tunning ¶

In [19]:
# defalut setting: This means that the model will use a "deviance" loss function, 
# a learning rate of 0.1, and 100 trees in the ensemble. 
#The model will also use a maximum depth of 3 for each tree and will split a node 
# if the impurity is above a certain threshold (as determined by the "friedman_mse" criterion).

# Set up the parameters for the gradient boosting model
parameters = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.05, 0.2]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Initialize the gradient boosting model
gbc_tuned = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state = 1)

# Set up the grid search cross-validation
grid_search = GridSearchCV(gbc_tuned, parameters, cv=4, scoring=scorer, return_train_score=True)

# Run the grid search
grid_search.fit(x_train,y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
gbc_tuned_2 = grid_search.best_estimator_


# Print the best hyperparameter values
print("Best parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Print the best cross-validation score
print("Best cross-validation score:", grid_search.best_score_)

Best parameters: {'learning_rate': 0.05, 'max_depth': 3, 'n_estimators': 200}

Best cross-validation score: 0.6075581395348837
